  After T18: zero live IPs в†’ program halts. Exit 0.

  Things to notice
  ----------------
  - Both `t` cells fire EXACTLY ONCE each. The IPs collide
    *just before* re-executing them, so no cascade.
  - The first collision happens at col 4 (where Cв‚Ѓ and Cв‚‚ meet)
    and the second at col 10 (where P and Cв‚ѓ meet вЂ” at tв‚‚'s
    own location). Different cells, different ticks, but both
    yield direction sum (0,0) в†’ die.
  - Asymmetric layout works because the SPACING between tв‚Ѓ,
    tв‚‚, and в†ђ is engineered so the timing equation works out.
    Specifically: tв‚‚ - tв‚Ѓ = в†ђ - tв‚‚ = 4 cells, which makes the
    later collisions land cleanly. Random asymmetric layouts
    cascade infinitely.
  - This is impossible in Befunge (no `t` SPLIT) and the
    timing is far harder to mentally simulate than a symmetric
    1-`t` puzzle.

  Compared to the easier `puzzle.wnd`
  -----------------------------------
  - puzzle.wnd: 1 t, 2 IPs, symmetric layout, 10 prints.
  - puzzle_hard.wnd: 2 t, 4 IPs, ASYMMETRIC layout, 10 prints.

  Same output length but the trace requires juggling four
  simultaneous IPs with distinct stacks instead of two.
